Here is example of how SWAT works:

# Python Workflow Example

```python
import pandas as pd
from swat import CAS

# 1. Connect to CAS (SAS Viya)
# Replace with your actual host, port, and credentials
conn = CAS('my-cas-host.example.com', 5570, 'username', 'password')

# 2. Upload Data
# Uploads a local pandas DataFrame to distributed CAS memory
df = pd.DataFrame({'Category': ['A', 'B', 'A', 'C'], 'Value': [10, 20, 30, 40]})
conn.upload_frame(df, casout={'name': 'my_data', 'replace': True})

# 3. Execute Analytics on Server
# This runs the 'summary' action on the SAS server
result = conn.simple.summary(table='my_data')

# 4. Retrieve Results
# Bring the specific result table back to Python as a DataFrame
summary_df = result['Summary']
print(summary_df)

# 5. Close Connection
conn.close()
```


# R Workflow Example

```r
library(swat)

# 1. Connect to CAS
conn <- CAS("my-cas-host.example.com", 5570, "username", "password")

# 2. Upload Data
df <- data.frame(Category = c('A', 'B', 'A'), Value = c(10, 20, 30))
cas.write.table(conn, df, casout = list(name="my_data", replace=TRUE))

# 3. Execute Analytics on Server
result <- cas.simple.summary(conn, table="my_data")

# 4. Retrieve Results
print(result$Summary)

# 5. Close Connection
cas.close(conn)
```
